<subSubSection lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="1803" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="28.[125,253,633,657]" box="[125,253,633,657]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">
<emphasis box="[125,253,633,657]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[125,1172,682,771]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">
New record: Bransfield Strait (Station B3: 
<specimenCount box="[631,797,682,706]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
). Previously recorded: Antarctic continent, South 
<collectingCountry box="[337,439,715,739]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">Shetland</collectingCountry>
and South 
<collectingCountry box="[589,768,715,739]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">Orkney Islands</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kott P" box="[789,919,715,739]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" pagination="121 - 182" refId="ref12998" refString="Kott P. 1954. Tunicata. Ascidians. Reports of the British, Australian and New Zealand Antarctic Research Expedition, 1929 - 1931, Series B (Zoology and Botany) 1 (4): 121 - 182." type="journal article" year="1954">Kott 1954</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kott P" box="[935,997,715,739]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" pagination="1 - 239" refId="ref13040" refString="Kott P. 1969. Antarctic Ascidiacea. Monographic account of the known species based on specimens collected under U. S. government auspices, 1947 - 1965. Antarctic Research Series 13: 1 - 239." type="book chapter" year="1969">1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Monniot C &amp; Monniot F" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" pagination="1 - 168" refId="ref14202" refString="Monniot C, Monniot F. 1983. Ascidies Antarctiques et Subantarctiques: Morphologie et Biogeographie. Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris 125: 1 - 168." type="journal article" year="1983">Monniot and Monniot 1983</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ramos-Espla AA &amp; Carcel JA &amp; Varela M" box="[312,605,747,771]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" pagination="215 - 223" refId="ref14516" refString="Ramos-Espla AA, Carcel JA, Varela M. 2005. Zoogeographical relationships of the littoral ascidiofauna around the Antarctic Peninsula, in the Scotia Arc and in the Magellan region. Scientia Marina 69 (2): 215 - 223." type="journal article" year="2005">Ramos-Esplá et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
); Tierra de Fuego (
<bibRefCitation author="Kott P" box="[834,963,747,771]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" pagination="11 - 82" refId="ref13079" refString="Kott P. 1971. Antarctic Ascidiacea II. Collections made south of 40 south latitude 1963 / 1967, principally by the U. S. N. S. Eltain. Antarctic Research Series 16 (4): 11 - 82." type="journal article" year="1971">Kott 1971</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[125,245,828,852]" box="[125,245,828,852]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">
<emphasis box="[125,245,828,852]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[125,1172,877,1225]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">
One ovoid colony, 
<quantity box="[358,438,877,901]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" unit="mm" value="21.0">21 mm</quantity>
height. The test is thin, but firm and tough. The surface is covered with minute papillae which contain, in the dorsal half of the body, calcareous spicules, typical of the species. Each spicule has numerous short spines in a slanting plane; near the siphons, the spicules are arranged with the oblique plane toward the siphon apertures. In the middle line of the body may be found a regular series of spine sizes, increasingly larger ones higher up.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[125,1172,877,1225]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">
Atrial and branchial siphons are almost sessile, bilabiate and directed anteriorly. There are 33 branched branchial tentacles of three sizes. The branchial sac has six very high folds on each side. The right gonad has split into two, although the ovaries are still fused together. The larger gonad has a double gonoduct (
<figureCitation box="[728,843,1169,1193]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="28.[137,197,1663,1682]" captionTargetBox="[232,1065,1297,1628]" captionTargetId="figure-281@28.[232,1066,1297,1628]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figure 18. Bathypera splendens. (a) Right gonad; (b) left gonad in curve of gut. Dark structures are the testes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5229571" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5229571/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">Figure 18</figureCitation>
). There is a large testis lobe on the distal end of each ovary and smaller lobes along it, arranged without order.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5229571" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5229571" box="[137,1162,1663,1682]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5229571/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" startId="28.[137,197,1663,1682]" targetBox="[232,1065,1297,1628]" targetPageId="28">
<paragraph blockId="28.[137,1162,1663,1682]" box="[137,1162,1663,1682]" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">
Figure 18. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Michaelsen" authorityYear="1904" box="[244,421,1663,1682]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis box="[244,421,1663,1682]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="1802">Bathypera splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. (a) Right gonad; (b) left gonad in curve of gut. Dark structures are the testes.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="29.[138,233,137,161]" box="[138,233,137,161]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803">
<emphasis box="[138,233,137,161]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[138,1185,185,371]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803">
<materialsCitation collectionCode="MNHN" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803" specimenCount="2">
Our specimen differs from the 
<typeStatus box="[548,597,185,209]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803">type</typeStatus>
specimen in the number of ovaries (one on each side in the 
<typeStatus box="[370,421,218,242]" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803">type</typeStatus>
) and the testis arrangement (many small lobes distributed along both sides of the ovary), but these kinds of variations are not unusual in deepsea species. However, in spite of these differences and after examining some specimens deposited at the 
<collectionCode box="[499,597,315,339]" country="France" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34988" name="Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803">MNHN</collectionCode>
, we concluded that our specimen belongs to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Michaelsen" authorityYear="1904" box="[138,273,347,371]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Bathypera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stolidobranchia" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis box="[138,273,347,371]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="1803">B. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
